.html|website=SpoilerTV|accessdate=October 3, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Goldbergs (2013 TV series)|The Goldbergs]]'' || Digby Yates || Episode: \"Food in a Geoffy\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Dawn|first=Randee|title=A mini-'Cheers' reunion is coming to TV! See the pics|url=https://www.today.com/today/amp/tdna162763|website=Today|accessdate=September 18, 2019|date=September 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2020 || ''[[Just Roll with It]]'' || Grandpa || 4 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Monsters at Work]]'' || Yeti, Bernard || Voice\n|}\n\n=== Video games ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#b0c4; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Title !! Voice role\n|-\n| 1995 || ''[[Toy Story (video game)|Toy Story]]'' || rowspan = \"5\" | Hamm\n|-\n| rowspan = \"2\" | 1996 || ''[[Disney's Activity Center|Toy Story: Activity Center]]''\n|-\n| ''[[Disney's Animated Storybook: Toy Story]]''\n|-\n| rowspan = \"2\" | 1999 || ''[[Disney's Activity Center|Toy Story 2: Activity Center]]''\n|-\n| ''[[Toy Story 2: Buzz Lightyear to the Rescue]]''<ref name=\"btva\"/>\n|-\n| rowspan = \"2\" | 2001 || ''[[Monsters, Inc. (video game)|Monsters, Inc.]]'' || Yeti\n|-\n| ''[[Toy Story Racer]]'' || rowspan = \"2\" | Hamm\n|-\n| 2003 || ''[[Disney's Extreme Skate Adventure]]''\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[Trivial Pursuit: Unhinged]]'' || Himself\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[The Incredibles: Rise of the Underminer]]'' || The Underminer\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Cars (video game)|Cars]]'' || rowspan = \"2\" | Mack\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Cars Race-O-Rama]]''\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Toy Story 3: The Video Game]]'' || rowspan = \"6\" | Hamm\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Kinect Rush: A Disney-Pixar Adventure]]''\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Disney Infinity (video game)|Disney Infinity]]''\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes]]''\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Disney Infinity 3.0]]''\n|-\n| 2016 || ''Disney Magic Kingdoms''\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Cars 3: Driven to Win]]'' || Mack\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Lego The Incredibles]]'' || Underminer\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Kingdom Hearts III]]''<ref name=\"btva\"/> || Hamm\n|}\n\n===Musical===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#b0c4; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2008\u201316 || ''[[Toy Story: The Musical]]'' || Hamm || Voice\n|}\n\n===Production credits===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#b0c4; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Title !! Position !! Notes\n|-\n| 1978 || ''[[Crown Court]]'' || rowspan = \"2\" | Writer || rowspan = \"3\" | 1 episode\n|-\n| 1980 || ''[[ITV Playhouse]]''\n|-\n| 1990 || ''[[Sydney (TV series)|Sydney]]'' || rowspan = \"4\" | Director\n|-\n| 1988\u201391 || ''[[Cheers (TV series)|Cheers]]'' || rowspan = \"2\" | 4 episodes\n|-\n| 1990, 1991 || ''Down Home''\n|-\n| rowspan = \"4\" | 1994 || ''[[Madman of the People]]'' || 3 episodes\n|-\n| ''Locals'' || Executive producer || TV Movie\n|-\n| ''[[Evening Shade]]'' || rowspan = \"3\" | Director || rowspan = \"3\" | 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Sister, Sister (TV series)|Sister, Sister]]''\n|-\n| 1996 || ''[[Pearl (TV series)|Pearl]]''\n|-\n| 1996 || ''The World's Most Incredible Animal Rescues'' || rowspan = \"4\" | Executive producer || rowspan = \"3\" | TV Special\n|-\n| 1997 || ''The World's Most Incredible Animal Rescues: Part 2''\n|-\n| 1998 || ''The World's Most Incredible Animal Rescues: Part 3''\n|-\n| 2010 || ''Industrial Tsunami'' || Documentary\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|John Ratzenberger}}\n* {{IMDb name|1652}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=158252|name=John Ratzenberger}}\n*[http://www.ratzenberger.com/ John Ratzenberger Official Website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ratzenberger, John}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American male video game actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Austrian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Hungarian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Connecticut Republicans]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Bridgeport, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:Sacred Heart University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = John Ratzenberger\n| image           = John Ratzenberger 2011 Shankbone.JPG\n| caption         = Ratzenberger at the 2011 [[Time 100]] gala\n| birth_name      = John Dezso Ratzenberger<ref name=\"about\" />\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1947|04|06}}\n| birth_place     = [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| residence       = [[Milford, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| other_names     = \n| alma_mater      = [[Sacred Heart University]]\n| occupation      = {{hlist|Actor|voice actor|director|producer|writer|entrepreneur}}\n| years_active    = 1975\u2013present\n| known_for       = [[Cliff Clavin]] in ''[[Cheers]]''<br />Various [[Pixar]] film roles\n| television      = ''[[Cheers]]''<br />''[[John Ratzenberger's Made in America]]''\n| spouse          = {{marriage|Georgia Stiny<br>|1982|2004|reason=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|Julie Blichfeldt<br>|2012}}\n| children        = 2\n| website         = {{URL|ratzenberger.com/}}\n| signature       =\n| imagesize       =\n}}\n\n'''John Dezso Ratzenberger''' (born April 6, 1947)<ref name=\"about\">[http://www.ratzenberger.com/about-john.php About John] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100409020908/http://www.ratzenberger.com/about-john.php |date=April 9, 2010 }} from Ratzenberger's official website</ref> is an American actor, voice actor, director, producer, writer and entrepreneur. He played [[Cliff Clavin]] on the TV show ''[[Cheers]]'', for which he earned two [[Emmy Award|Emmy]] nominations, and plays voice roles in every [[Pixar|Pixar Animation Studios]] film, including [[Hamm (Toy Story)|Hamm]] in the [[Toy Story (franchise)|''Toy Story'' franchise]], [[The Underminer]] in [[The Incredibles (franchise)|''The Incredibles'' franchise]], and [[Mack (Cars)|Mack]] in the [[Cars (franchise)|''Cars'' franchise]]. He is the only voice actor to appear in every Pixar feature film, and with minor appearances in major films such as ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'' and ''[[The Empire Strikes Back]]'', he is one of the [[List of highest grossing actors|most successful actors]] of all time in terms of box-office receipts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/stacey-alcorn/john-ratzenberger--americ_b_9599966.html|title=John Ratzenberger - American Made|last=Alcorn|first=Stacey|date=2016-04-02|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-30}}</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]], Ratzenberger began his entertainment career while living in London in the 1970s. He had minor film and television roles throughout the late 70s and early 1980s before creating, and then landing, the role of the know-it-all mailman Cliff Clavin on ''Cheers'' (1982\u20131993), a role he portrayed throughout the show's eleven seasons. His first Pixar role was the voice of Hamm in ''[[Toy Story]]'' (1995), and he has voiced Pixar characters in films and video games ever since. From 2004 to 2008 he hosted the TV documentary series ''[[Made in America (TV program)|Made in America]]''. Outside of acting, he has promoted American entrepreneurship and manufacturing, and campaigned for several [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidates.\n\n== Early life ==\nRatzenberger was born on [[Easter Sunday]], April 6, 1947,<ref>[http://tlarsen2.tripod.com/thomaslarsen/easterdates.html#List19 List of Easter Sunday Dates 1900-1999]</ref>  in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]], the son of Bertha Veronica Ratzenberger (n\u00e9e Grochowski), who worked for [[Remington Arms]], and Dezso Alexander Ratzenberger, a [[Texaco]] truck driver.<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/91/John-Ratzenberger.html John Ratzenberger Biography (1947\u2013)<!-- Bot generated title -->] from filmreference.com</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1545936_20015453,00.html|title=Last Night's Dancing with the Stars: What You Didn't See|work=PEOPLE.com}}</ref> His father was of Austrian and [[Hungarian American|Hungarian]] descent, and his mother was of [[Polish American|Polish]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ratzenberger.net/genealogy/databases/descendants_of_daniel_ratzenberger/d1.htm#i551|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012165535/http://www.ratzenberger.net/genealogy/databases/descendants_of_daniel_ratzenberger/d1.htm#i551|url-status=dead|archive-date=2008-10-12|title=The Ratzenberger Attic|publisher=}}</ref> He attended St. Ann's School in Bridgeport and [[Sacred Heart University]] in Fairfield, Connecticut.<ref name=\"about\" /> In 1969, Ratzenberger was a tractor operator at the [[Woodstock Festival]].<ref>{{cite video|people       =|date       =May 8, 2008|title       =The Mark Levin Show|url       =mms://abcrad.wmod.llnwd.net/a49/external/0102cABAAHQAAAAcDle6yKhvE1c0LnEJnNwFajD8QD92LOnSD/levin/levin_insider/levin05082008.wma|format       =wma|medium       =Radio|accessdate       =December 6, 2008|time       =|id       =|isbn       =|oclc       =|quote       =}}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He moved to London in 1971 and stayed there for 10 years.<ref name=\"about\" />\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:John Ratzenberger at the 1992 Emmy Awards (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=.66|left|Ratzenberger at the 1992 Emmy Awards]]\nRatzenberger was a house [[framer]]<ref name=scifiwire>{{cite news|first=Ian|last=Spelling|title=John Ratzenberger, Pixar's good luck charm, on Up, Bugs and Toys 3|work=[[Sci Fi Wire]]|date=May 21, 2009|url=http://scifiwire.com/2009/05/john-ratzenberger-pixars.php|accessdate=May 22, 2009}}</ref> living in London when he began his career in the performing arts.<ref name=\"about\" /> Through the 1970s, he performed with Ray Hassett as the comedic theatrical duo Sal's Meat Market, which toured across the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unfinishedhistories.com/history/companies/sals-meat-market/ |title=Sal's Meat Market | work=Unfinishedhistories.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-20}}</ref> [[Peter Richardson (British director)|Peter Richardson]] and [[Nigel Planer]] as ''The Outer Limits'' and in ''[[The Comic Strip]]'' were heavily influenced by Sal's Meat Market.<ref name= Wilmut-1989>{{cite book|last=Wilmut|first= Roger|title=Didn't You Kill My Mother in Law?- the story of alternative comedy in Britain from the Comedy Store to Saturday Night Live|year=1989|publisher=Methuen|location=UK|isbn=0-413-17390-9|page=58|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Didn_t_you_kill_my_mother_in_law.html?id=mrQqAAAAMAAJ}}</ref> His first role was a patron in ''[[The Ritz (film)|The Ritz]]'' (1976). Throughout the late 1970s and early 1980s, Ratzenberger appeared in various minor roles in major feature films, including'' [[Firefox (film)|Firefox]]''; ''[[A Bridge Too Far (1977 film)|A Bridge Too Far]]'', as Lieutenant [[James Megellas]]; ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'', as a missile controller; ''[[Superman II]]'', as the [[NASA]] control man; ''[[The Empire Strikes Back|Star Wars: The Empire Strikes Back]]'' as Major [[List of Star Wars characters#D|Derlin]]; ''[[Motel Hell]]'' as a drummer; [[Outland (film)|''Outland'']] as a doomed mine worker named Tarlow; and ''[[Gandhi (film)|Gandhi]]'', playing an American lieutenant (Ratzenberger's voice was dubbed over by an uncredited voice actor).\n\n=== ''Cheers'' ===\nRatzenberger played mail carrier [[Cliff Clavin]] on the sitcom ''[[Cheers]]''. He had read for the part of [[Norm Peterson]], but after the audition, he sensed that they were not going to give him the part. Sensing an opportunity, he asked if they had written a bar know-it-all, which the producers decided was a great idea.<ref>''Toasting Cheers'', Dennis A. Bjorklund, p.7</ref> Ratzenberger also came up with the idea for Cliff's trademark white socks, which he wore as a tribute to French comedian [[Jacques Tati]].<ref name=\"joecookprogram.wordpress.com\">The Joe Cook Program (Radio). July 26, 2012. http://joecookprogram.wordpress.com/2012/07/26/john-ratzenberger-interview/ Retrieved July 29, 2012.</ref> Cliff became known for his outlandish stories of plausible half-truths, uninteresting trivia, and misinformation, and in general for being a pretentious blowhard. Cliff and Norm, the primary customer characters, became iconic bar buddies. Ratzenberger provided the voice for an animated version of Cliff on [[The Simpsons (season 6)|''The Simpsons'' sixth-season]] episode \"[[Fear of Flying (The Simpsons)|Fear of Flying]]\". Ratzenberger was nominated for an [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series|Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series]] in 1985 and again in 1986.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/1985/outstanding-supporting-actor-in-a-comedy-series|title=Nominees/Winners|work=Television Academy|access-date= 2018-01-30|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/1986/outstanding-supporting-actor-in-a-comedy-series|title= Nominees/Winners|work=Television Academy|access-date=2018-01-30|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Paramount Television]] licensed the look of the Cheers bar to the Host International subsidiary of [[Host Marriott Services]] for use in airports in the U.S. and New Zealand, the group also created [[animatronic]] barflies. They were called \"Hank\" and \"Bob\"; Ratzenberger and [[George Wendt]] claimed Hank and Bob resembled them, and in January 1993, sued Host for using their likenesses without permission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/print?id=115037|title=Norm and Cliff Fight Cheers Robots|work=go.com}}</ref> The case languished in court for eight years before all sides settled in 2001.<ref>[http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,131242,00.html Bar Association Plus, Norm and Cliff settle ''Cheers'' robot lawsuit] from the ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' website</ref>\n\n=== Pixar ===\nRatzenberger has had a voice part in all of [[List of Pixar films|Pixar's feature films]], ranging from main characters to characters who appear in only one scene.<ref>[http://www.slate.com/id/2257378/ \"Pixar's secret weapon: John Ratzenberger], Slate.com</ref> His roles include:\n*[[Hamm the toy|Hamm]] in the [[Toy Story (franchise)|''Toy Story'' series]] ([[Toy Story|1995]], [[Toy Story 2|1999]], [[Toy Story 3|2010]], [[Toy Story 4|2019]])\n*P.T. Flea, the Circus Ring Leader in ''[[A Bug's Life]]'' (1998)\n*[[Yeti|The Abominable Snowman]] in the [[Monsters, Inc. (franchise)|''Monsters, Inc.'' series]] ([[Monsters, Inc.|2001]], [[Monsters University|2013]])\n*The school of [[Silver moony|Moonfish]] in ''[[Finding Nemo]]'' (2003)\n*[[The Underminer]] in [[The Incredibles (franchise)|''The Incredibles'' series]] ([[The Incredibles|2004]], [[Incredibles 2|2018]])\n*[[Mack (Cars)|Mack the truck]] in the [[Cars (franchise)|''Cars'' series]] ([[Cars (film)|2006]], [[Cars 2|2011]], [[Cars 3|2017]])\n*Mustafa the [[waiter]] in ''[[Ratatouille (film)|Ratatouille]]'' (2007)\n*John in ''[[WALL-E]]'' (2008)\n*Tom the [[construction worker]] in ''[[Up (2009 film)|Up]]'' (2009)\n*Gordon the guard in ''[[Brave (2012 film)|Brave]]'' (2012)\n*Fritz in ''[[Inside Out (2015 film)|Inside Out]]'' (2015)\n*Earl the [[Velociraptor]] in ''[[The Good Dinosaur]]'' (2015)\n*Bill the [[crab]] in ''[[Finding Dory]]'' (2016)\n*Juan Ortodoncia in ''[[Coco (2017 film)|Coco]]'' (2017)\n*Fenwick the construction worker in ''[[Onward (film)|Onward]]'' (2020)\n*TBA in ''[[Soul (2020 film)|Soul]]'' (2020)\nRatzenberger's tenure at Pixar was parodied during the end credits of ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]'', where his character, Mack, watches car-themed versions of Pixar films (''[[Toy Story|Toy Car Story]]'', ''[[Monsters, Inc.|Monster Trucks, Inc.]]'', and ''[[A Bug's Life]]'', the latter of which references the [[Volkswagen Beetle]]). Mack notes that all the characters Ratzenberger has played were excellent until he realizes that they are performed by the same actor, at which point he remarks, \"They're just using the same actor over and over,\" and asks, \"What kind of cut-rate production is this?!\"\n\nHis favorite of his Pixar characters was P.T. Flea, because \"in real life, I always get a kick out of those kinds of characters, people who just go into a rage for [no] explicable reason. He was always on edge. His [[blood pressure]] was always way over the top, and everything that he did was done in a panicked state. So it was a lot of fun to play him.\"<ref name= scifiwire /> Although technically not Pixar films, Ratzenberger voiced Harland the jet tug in [[DisneyToon Studios]]' ''[[Planes (film)|Planes]]'' (2013)<ref name=\"SKStills\">{{cite news|title=Disney's \"Planes\" Hi-res Stills, Fun Facts and Activity Sheets|url=http://www.stitchkingdom.com/disney-planes-stills-fun-facts-activity-sheets-62551/|accessdate= May 11, 2013|newspaper=Stitch Kingdom|date=May 9, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130630145040/http://www.stitchkingdom.com/disney-planes-stills-fun-facts-activity-sheets-62551/|archive-date=June 30, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=JHMPremiere>{{cite news|last=Hill|first=Jim|title=World premiere of Disney \"Planes\" turns Hollywood Boulevard into a celebrity-filled landing strip|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2013/08/06/disney-quot-planes-quot-world-premiere.aspx|accessdate=January 24, 2014|newspaper=Jim Hill Media|date=August 6, 2013}}</ref> and a mustached plane named Brodi in its sequel, ''[[Planes: Fire & Rescue]]'' (2014),<ref name= BFIPlanes2>{{cite web|title=Planes Fire & Rescue (2014)|url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/53c99d98514fb|publisher=British Film Institute| accessdate= August 24, 2014}}</ref> both of which are set in Pixar's [[Cars (franchise)|''Cars'' franchise]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2013/03/25/planes-dane-cook/1998599/|title=Look! Up in the sky! It's an exclusive peek at 'Planes'!| work= USA Today}}</ref> Additionally, Ratzenberger will reprise his role as The Abominable Snowman in the [[Disney+]]-exclusive series ''[[Monsters at Work]]'', which is set after ''Monsters Inc.''<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/monsters-voice-cast-return-disney-series-1200367 'Monsters, Inc.' Voice Cast to Return for Disney+ Series (Exclusive)]</ref>\n\n=== Reality show appearances ===\nDuring season six of ''[[Last Comic Standing]]'', Ratzenberger was a talent scout with his former ''Cheers'' co-star George Wendt.\n\nOn March 2, 2007, he replaced [[Vincent Pastore]] (who had quit after one week of training) on the [[Dancing with the Stars (US season 4)|fourth season of the American version]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (US TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''.<ref name= \"dancing\">{{cite news|title='Dancing' adds Cliff from 'Cheers' |url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/SHOWBIZ/TV/03/02/people.ratzenberger.ap/index.html |agency=Associated Press |publisher= CNN |date=February 20, 2007 |accessdate=March 2, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070304064956/http://www.cnn.com/2007/SHOWBIZ/TV/03/02/people.ratzenberger.ap/index.html |archivedate= March 4, 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> He was partnered with professional ballroom dancer [[Edyta Sliwinska]], who had been Pastore's partner; the two were the sixth couple to be eliminated from the show.\n\nOn December 3, 2009, Ratzenberger appeared on an episode of ''[[American Chopper]]'' to help promote awareness of the Iraq Star Foundation.\n\nOn June 26, 2011, Ratzenberger was asked by NASCAR to give the shouting command for the [[2011 Toyota/Save Mart 350|2011 Toyota Save-Mart 350]] at [[Sonoma Raceway]]. Ratzenberger accepted and gave the \"Gentlemen, start your engines\" command.\n\nOn April 23, 2015, Ratzenberger appeared as a guest judge on the [[Hell's Kitchen (U.S. season 14)|14th season]] of ''[[Hell's Kitchen (U.S. TV series)|Hell's Kitchen]]'' for an alcohol challenge, in nod to his role on ''[[Cheers]]''.\n\n=== Additional voice, TV, and film work ===\n*Guest starred as Walter Brewster in an episode of ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]'' in 1984 \n* Appeared in the sitcom ''[[Sabrina the Teenage Witch (1996 TV series)|Sabrina the Teenage Witch]]'' as ''Bob'' or Santa Claus (1997)\n* Hosted the [[Travel Channel]] TV series ''[[John Ratzenberger's Made in America]]'', about things made in the USA ({{As of|2003|alt=2003\u20132008}})\n* Guest-starred in four episodes of the first season of [[John Ritter]]'s sitcom ''[[8 Simple Rules]]'' as Paul Hennessy's overly friendly neighbor Fred Doyle\n* Hosts the Wildcard section in the PC version of the board game ''[[Trivial Pursuit]]''\n* Also appeared on ''[[That '70s Show]]'' as Glen, a man stuck in an awful marriage with his high-school sweetheart whose negative example gives Eric second thoughts about marrying Donna\n* Played Thomas Foy in the TV movie ''The Pennsylvania Miners' Story''\n* As Shelly Cole star in ''[[The Village Barbershop]]'' (2008), written and directed by Chris Ford<ref name=Village>{{cite web|url= http://www.thevillagebarbershop.com/ |title= The Village Barbershop| website= thevillagebarbershop.com |date= |accessdate= 2018-04-02}}</ref>\n* An appearance in ''[[Bill Nye the Science Guy]]''\n* Provided the voice of Rigger in the animated series ''[[Captain Planet and the Planeteers]]''\n* Made an appearance on British show ''[[Live from Studio Five]]'' (February 17, 2010).\n* Appeared in television commercials for the [[Pitney Bowes]] personal post office, ended every commercial saying \"Hey, I look good in red!\"\n* Appeared in commercials for [[Choice Hotels#Brands|Quality Hotels]] and [[Zaxby's]] restaurant chain (2010)\n* Plays Mike the Angel in ''[[What If... (2010 film)|What If...]]'', a [[Pure Flix Entertainment]]/Jenkins Entertainment movie release in 2010, also starring Kevin Sorbo, Kristy Swanson, and Debby Ryan<ref name=WhatIf>{{cite web|url=http://thewhatifmovie.com/|title=\u80b2\u6bdb\u3084\u767a\u6bdb\u306b\u52b9\u679c\u304c\u3042\u308b\u30b7\u30e3\u30f3\u30d7\u30fc\u306e\u7a2e\u985e\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066\u30f0\u30df\u30bc\u30a5|work=thewhatifmovie.com}}</ref>\n* Reprised his role of Cliff Clavin in an episode of ''[[Frasier]]''<ref name=\"Frasier\">{{cite episode |network=NBC |title= Cheerful Goodbyes |series= Frasier | season=9 |number= 21|date=April 30, 2002 |oclc= 124055292}}</ref> and - along with his ''Cheers'' partner, George Wendt - an episode of ''[[Wings (1990 TV series)|Wings]]'' called \"[[List of Wings episodes|The Story of Joe]]\"\n* Hosted the documentary ''Industrial Tsunami'', intended to wake Americans up to the shortage of skilled workers threatening the existence of American companies and entire industries\n* Appeared in the final episode of ''[[Secret Army (TV series)|Secret Army]]'' entitled \"The Execution\" as a Canadian officer who is bribed by Standartenfuhrer Kessler's mistress Madeleine Duclos to spring Kessler from the POW camp where he is incarcerated\n* Starred in \"A House Divided,\" the 28th episode of the first season of ''[[Melissa & Joey]]'' as Arnie the neighbor\n* Voiced the bathhouse's assistant manager, Aniyaku, in the English [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dub]] of ''[[Spirited Away]]''\n* Made a cameo in the DisneyToon Studios animation ''[[Planes (film)|Planes]]'' (2013) playing Harland the pushback vehicle\n* Made commercials for Ontario's [[The Beer Store]] with his ''Cheers'' partner, George Wendt\n* Appeared in ''[[Drop Dead Diva]]'' as Kim Kaswell's estranged father\n*Will reprise the role of The Abominable Snowman in the TV Series ''Monsters at Work.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/monsters-voice-cast-return-disney-series-1200367|title='Monsters, Inc.' Voice Cast to Return for Disney+ Series (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Other work ==\n[[File:JohnRatzenberger08RIIFF.jpg|thumb|Ratzenberger at the 2008 [[Rhode Island International Film Festival]]]]\nRatzenberger developed a packaging-alternatives product made from biodegradable and non-toxic recycled paper as a safe alternative to [[foam peanut]]s and plastic bubble wrap. This product was manufactured by his company Eco-Pak Industries, which he later sold.<ref name=Peanuts>[http://www.ratzenberger.com/about-john.php About John: Innovator] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100409020908/http://www.ratzenberger.com/about-john.php |date=April 9, 2010 }} from Ratzenberger's official website</ref>\n\nRatzenberger co-authored ''We've Got it Made in America: A Common Man's Salute to an Uncommon Country'' ({{ISBN|1-931722-84-6}}), published in 2006.\n\nHe also co-founded the Nuts, Bolts and Thingamajigs Foundation,<ref>[http://www.nutsandboltsfoundation.org/ Official website] of the Nuts, Bolts & Thingamajigs Foundation</ref> dedicated to raising awareness among young people of skilled trades and engineering disciplines.<ref>\"Early recruitment: Foundation draws youth to careers in manufacturing\". ''Industrial Engineer''. May 2009. p. 12.</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Ratzenberger became affiliated with and now represents the Center for America (formerly the Foundation for Fair Civil Justice) to further develop his work and increase awareness about the skilled worker shortage facing the United States and the changes needed to positively impact and increase the number of skilled workers.<ref name=Ratz2>{{cite web|url=http://www.ratzenberger.com|title=John Ratzenberger \u2013 Fiddlers Bay Productions|work=ratzenberger.com}}</ref> He joined as a board member in 2010.<ref name=Ratz2 /> CFA is a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization whose mission is to \"educate, motivate, and empower the American people to understand they have the greatest stake in removing obstacles to a fair civil justice system, innovation, entrepreneurism, and job creation.\"<ref name=FFCJ>{{cite web|url=http://www.foundationforfairciviljustice.org/site/about/|title=foundationforfairciviljustice.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101119044935/http://www.foundationforfairciviljustice.org/site/about/|archivedate=November 19, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> CFA creates multi-media educational programs, publications, and website features that reach millions of Americans through radio, television, and the internet.\"<ref name=\"FFCJ\" />\n\nIn 2016, Ratzenberger launched thegiftbox.com,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/actor-john-ratzenberger-launches-thegiftboxcom-300373638.html|title=Actor John Ratzenberger Launches TheGiftBox.com|last=TheGiftBox.com|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2017-01-18}}</ref> an e-commerce website that allows customers to subscribe to a variety of monthly boxes.\n\n== Personal life ==\nRatzenberger has two children, James John (born 1987), and Nina Kathrine (born 1989), both from a 19-year marriage to Georgia Stiny that ended in divorce in 2004.\n\nAfter dating for nearly four years, Ratzenberger married Julie Blichfeldt on November 6, 2012.<ref name=UPIMarriedJulie>{{cite web|title=John Ratzenberger weds Julie Blichfeldt|url=http://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2012/11/30/John-Ratzenberger-weds-Julie-Blichfeldt/UPI-23841354326181/|publisher=UPI|accessdate=September 19, 2014|date=November 30, 2012}}</ref> Both Ratzenberger and Blichfeldt are described as \"avid outdoors enthusiasts, philanthropists, and activists\".<ref name=UPIMarriedJulie />\n\n== Political views ==\nRatzenberger, a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], said he considered [[United States Senate election in Connecticut, 2012|running for the U.S. Senate in Connecticut in 2012]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/69137852.html?page=1&c=y|title=Pawlenty draws wallets fat ... and famous|author=Rachel E. Stassen-Berger|work=[[Star Tribune|Minneapolis Star Tribune]]|date=November 5, 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 presidential race]], Ratzenberger [[John McCain 2008 presidential campaign|campaigned]] for [[John McCain]], appearing with former ''Cheers'' co-star [[Kelsey Grammer]] at several Republican party events.<ref>John Ratzenberger and [[Kelsey Grammer]] greeted McCain supporters, called voters on behalf of the Republican ticket, participated in voter-registration activities at the local campaign headquarters, and held a McCain victory rally in [[Henderson, Nevada]]. {{cite news|url=http://www.lvrj.com/news/30835704.html|title= Political emissaries descend on valley: Richardson, Grammer rally voters at events|publisher=[[Las vegas review journal|Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|date=October 11, 2008|accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kvbc.com/Global/story.asp?S=9161824&nav=15MUUi4B|title= Stars stump in Las Vegas Valley|publisher= [[NBC]]-affiliated [[KSNV-DT|KVBC]] website|date=October 11, 2008|accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref> He also has been outspoken in opposition of the [[Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act of 2010|2010 health care reform bill]], referring to it as [[socialism]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/11/05/tea-party-activists-hit-the-hill-arrested-outside-pelosis-office/|title= Tea Party activists hit the Hill, arrested outside Pelosi's office|publisher= CNN Political Ticker|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=November 5, 2009}}</ref> He endorsed [[Mitt Romney]] in [[2012 United States presidential election|2012]].<ref>[https://archive.is/20130128150443/http://www.mercurynews.com/news/ci_21877306/obama-romney-turn-star-power-help-nv Obama, Romney turn to star power for help in NV \u2013 San Jose Mercury News]</ref> He appeared on ''[[Your World|Your World with Neil Cavuto]]'' to support [[Donald Trump]]'s [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|candidacy]] during the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential race]], shortly after Trump was declared the presumptive Republican nominee.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://insider.foxnews.com/2016/05/11/pixar-voice-actor-john-ratzenberger-supports-donald-trump|title='The Only Candidate for Me': Pixar Icon Throws Support Behind Donald Trump|publisher=Fox News Insider|date=May 11, 2016|accessdate=November 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 2010, he appeared and endorsed [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]] for the United States Senate at [[Mechanics Hall (Worcester, Massachusetts)|Mechanics Hall]] in [[Worcester, Massachusetts]].\n\nRatzenberger campaigned for Republican [[Josh Mandel]] of Ohio for the State Treasurer position during the 2010 election and on January 10, 2011, served as master of ceremonies for Mandel's swearing into office.\n\nIn response to the [[2012 Aurora, Colorado shooting]], he said, \"Hollywood has to, at some point, admit that what they produce does affect the minds of people.... If you just want to shock 'em... society will pay the price for that at some point.\"<ref name=\"joecookprogram.wordpress.com\" />\n\n==Filmography==\n\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 1976 || ''[[The Ritz (film)|The Ritz]]'' || Patron ||\n|-\n| rowspan = \"3\" |1977 || ''[[Twilight's Last Gleaming]]'' || Sgt. Kopecki ||\n|-\n| ''[[A Bridge Too Far (film)|A Bridge Too Far]]'' || Lt. [[James Megellas]] ||\n|-\n| ''[[Valentino (1977 film)|Valentino]]'' || Newshound ||\n|-\n| rowspan = \"2\" | 1978 || ''[[Warlords of Atlantis]]'' || Fenn ||\n|-\n| ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'' || Missile cont